          <br>
          <p> <strong>In addition, the average RTP for slots offered by the
              Oregon lottery is 92.3%,</strong> as listed below.</p>
          <p><strong>These payouts and RTPs are significant, because in <a =
href=3D"https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2025/02/07/super-bowl-sport=
s-betting/" target=3D"_blank">a
                Washington Post article</a> (which cited the article you=E2=
=80=99re
              reading now as a source for slot returns), </strong>George Wi=
ll
            said that the ~40% house edge from state-run lotteries vs. the =
~15%
            from private slot machines =E2=80=9Cproves again that the priva=
te sector is
            preferable.=E2=80=9D </p>
          <p><strong>As usual, George Will is wrong.</strong>&nbsp; He=E2=
=80=99s
            comparing apples to oranges, because the games he=E2=80=99s com=
paring are
            radically different.&nbsp; The proper comparisons would be the
            returns from public vs. private slot machines, or public vs. pr=
ivate
            lotteries.&nbsp; And as we just saw, slots in government-run ca=
sinos
            pay about the same as private-sector ones.</p>
          <p>When there=E2=80=99s a flood and George Will is stuck on his r=
oof, will he
            expect the free market to save him?&nbsp; It=E2=80=99ll more li=
kely be FEMA.</p>
          <p> </p>
          <p>While we=E2=80=99re on the subject of public vs. private, it=
=E2=80=99s worth noting
            that as of July 2022, three states (IL, IN, NJ) had privatized =
the
            operation of their lotteries. <cite>(<a href=3D"https://cnsmary=
land.org/2022/07/01/state-lotteries-are-increasingly-ceding-control-to-comp=
anies/" target=3D"_blank">Howard
                Center</a>)</cite>&nbsp; </p>
          <p><br>
          </p>
          <p></p>
          <br>
          <h2>TV, movie, and celebrity-themed slots pay worse</h2>
          <p>A former slot director notes, "TV, movie, and celebrity themed
            games...cost the casino more in revenue sharing (they also cant=
 be
            purchased), so the hold is always higher."<cite>(<a href=3D"htt=
ps://wizardofvegas.com/forum/gambling/slots/32214-how-to-guesstimate-slot-m=
achine-payback-percentage/#post692694" target=3D"_blank">source</a>)</cite>=
&nbsp;
            A VP at a slot maker suggests that these slots pay about 2% poi=
nts
            less than non-themed slots. <cite>(<a href=3D"https://lasvegass=
un.com/news/2017/may/11/5-slot-myths-why-what-you-think-you-know-is-wrong/"=
 target=3D"_blank">LV
                Sun</a>)</cite>&nbsp; </p>
          <p><br>
          </p>
          <h2>Online slot returns</h2>
          <p><strong>Online casinos offer much better slot returns than lan=
d
              casinos,</strong> because they have much lower overhead.&nbsp=
; (No
            physical machines, no luxury resort to make mortgage payments o=
n,
            fewer employees, etc.)&nbsp; Slot returns in <strong>land casin=
os
              are around 91%</strong> (see above) but <strong>online it's a=
bout
              96%</strong> (which is my estimate for my advertiser, <strong=
><a href=3D"https://record.revenuenetwork.com/_NWwK_7xQ8zrAYeZOCF1xZWNd7Zgq=
dRLk/1/" rel=3D"sponsored">Bovada
                Online Casino</a></strong>).</p>
          <p><strong>This is a big deal:</strong>&nbsp; At 91% RTP you're l=
osing
            <strong>9%</strong> of your money, and at 96% RTP you're losing=
 <strong>4%</strong>
            of your money.&nbsp; So, by switching from land casinos to onli=
ne,
            your money will last twice as long (with the catch being that y=
ou
            could lose more online if the easy access to online gambling ca=
uses
            you to play more).</p>
          <p><strong>While it's nearly impossible to find the RTP for speci=
fic
              machines in land casinos, </strong>there are a number of onli=
ne
            slot publishers and casinos which publish that data.&nbsp; I
            tabulated the data from one online publisher (NetEnt) and here =
are
            the results:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>89% of their slots are in the range <strong>96-96.99%</stro=
ng>.</li>
